Plot severity of crime and sentence length

scatterplot <- ggpairs(sentence, columns = c("primlev", "years"),
                       upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size=3)),
title = "Scatterplot matrix of primlev and years")
print(scatterplot, progress=FALSE)

Format the variables

sentence <- mutate(sentence, lnyears = log(years), primlev0 = primlev - 1, primlev02 = primlev0^2)

Plot severity of crime and log of sentence length

scatterplot2 <- ggpairs(sentence, columns = c("primlev0", "lnyears"),
                       upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size=3)),
title = "Scatterplot matrix of primlev0 and lnyears")
print(scatterplot2, progress=FALSE)

Create plot of primlev0 and lnyears with loess smooth

ggplot(data = sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Bivariate plot with loess smooth")

The relationship between primlev0 and lnyears appears to be curvilinear such that the relationship is more extreme when the severity of the crime was higher.

Create a plot of primlev0 and lnyears with straight line

ggplot(data = sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Bivariate plot with straight line")

The stright line seems to fit the data relatively well but it does not always capture the density of the y variable at each level of the x variable.

Create plot of primlev0 and lnyears with quadratic function

ggplot(data = sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Bivariate plot with quadratic function")

This plot looks similar to the loess smooth line.

Interpret quadratic model

Calculate the changing slope of primlev0

# Slope at primlev0 = 3 
-0.193 + (2*.048*3)
[1] 0.095
# Slope at primlev0 = 6 
-0.193 + (2*.048*6)
[1] 0.383
# Slope at primlev0 = 9 
-0.193 + (2*.048*9)
[1] 0.671

Interpret regression slopes in terms of percent change in years

ln.y <- function(slope, x_chg) {
  new_slope <- 100 * (exp(slope * x_chg) - 1)
  return(new_slope)
}
ln.y(slope = .095, x_chg = 1)
[1] 9.965886
ln.y(slope = .383, x_chg = 1)
[1] 46.6678
ln.y(slope = .671, x_chg = 1)
[1] 95.61925
